Note: Additional utility functions continue with similar pattern...
Process called "calculate_allocations_per_second" that takes pattern as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate actual allocations per second from pattern data
            Let time_span_seconds be (TimeCore.get_system_time_nanoseconds - pattern["first_seen"]) / 1000000000
    If time_span_seconds < or equal to 0:
            Return 0
            Return pattern["call_count"] / time_span_seconds

Process called "calculate_allocation_efficiency" that takes pattern as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate allocation efficiency based on usage patterns
            Let average_allocation be pattern["total_allocations"] / pattern["call_count"]
    Let efficiency_threshold be 1048576 Note: 1MB
    If average_allocation < or equal to efficiency_threshold:
            Return 1.0
    Otherwise:
            Return efficiency_threshold / average_allocation

Process called "determine_optimization_potential" that takes pattern as Dictionary[String, Any] returns OptimizationPotential:
    Note: Determine optimization potential based on allocation patterns
            Let average_allocation be pattern["total_allocations"] / pattern["call_count"]
    Let call_frequency be pattern["call_count"] If average_allocation > 10485760 and call_frequency > 100: Note: >10MB and >100 calls
            Return High
    Otherwise if average_allocation > 1048576 and call_frequency > 50: Note: >1MB and >50 calls
            Return Medium
    Otherwise if average_allocation > 102400 and call_frequency > 10: Note: >100KB and >10 calls
            Return Low
    Otherwise:
            Return None

Process called "calculate_memory_growth_rate" that takes samples as List[Integer] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate actual memory growth rate from samples
    If length of samples < 2:
            Return 0.0 Let first_sample be samples[0]
            Let last_sample be samples[length of samples - 1]
    Let sample_count be length of samples Note: Estimate time span (assuming 1ms per sample)
    Let time_span_seconds be sample_count / 1000.0 If time_span_seconds < or equal to 0.0:
            Return 0.0 Let growth_bytes be last_sample - first_sample
            Return growth_bytes / time_span_seconds

Process called "calculate_gc_pressure" that takes peak_memory as Integer returns Float:
    Note: Calculate garbage collection pressure based on memory usage
    Let system_memory_limit be 2147483648 Note: 2GB typical limit
    Let pressure_ratio be peak_memory / system_memory_limit If pressure_ratio > 0.9:
    Return 1.0 Note: Very high pressure
    Otherwise if pressure_ratio > 0.7:
    Return 0.8 Note: High pressure
    Otherwise if pressure_ratio > 0.5:
    Return 0.5 Note: Medium pressure
    Otherwise:
    Return pressure_ratio Note: Low pressure

Process called "calculate_fragmentation_score" that takes samples as List[Integer] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate memory fragmentation score from allocation patterns
    If length of samples < 3:
            Return 0.0 Let variance be calculate_variance with samples as samples
    Let mean be calculate_average with values as samples If mean < or equal to 0:
    Return 0.0 Note: Coefficient of variation as fragmentation indicator
    Let cv be variance / (mean * mean) Note: Normalize to 0-1 scale
    If cv > 1.0:
            Return 1.0
    Otherwise:
            Return cv

Process called "calculate_memory_efficiency" that takes peak_memory as Integer and allocation_patterns as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate overall memory efficiency
            Let total_allocations be 0
    Let allocation_count be 0 For each function_name and pattern in allocation_patterns:
            Set total_allocations to total_allocations pattern["total_allocations"]
    Set allocation_count to allocation_count pattern["call_count"] If total_allocations < or equal to 0:
    Return 1.0 Note: Efficiency = useful memory / peak memory
    Let useful_memory_ratio be total_allocations / peak_memory If useful_memory_ratio > 1.0:
            Return 1.0
    Otherwise:
            Return useful_memory_ratio

Process called "calculate_stack_memory_usage" that takes frames as List[TracebackCore.StackFrame] returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate estimated stack memory usage
    Let estimated_frame_size be 256 Note: Typical stack frame size in bytes
    Let total_stack_memory be length of frames * estimated_frame_size Note: Add memory for local variables
    For each frame in frames:
            Let local_var_count be length of frame.local_variables
    Let estimated_var_size be 64 Note: Average variable size
            Set total_stack_memory to total_stack_memory (local_var_count * estimated_var_size) Return total_stack_memory

Process called "calculate_heap_memory_usage" that takes frames as List[TracebackCore.StackFrame] returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate estimated heap memory usage from frames
    Let total_heap_memory be 0 For each frame in frames:
            Set total_heap_memory to total_heap_memory frame.memory_usage_bytes Return total_heap_memory

Process called "determine_overall_risk_level" that takes issues as List[SecurityIssue] returns RiskLevel:
    If length of issues > 5:
            Return Critical
    Otherwise if length of issues > 2:
            Return High
    Otherwise if length of issues > 0:
            Return Medium
    Otherwise:
            Return Low

Process called "calculate_security_score" that takes issues as List[SecurityIssue] and exposed_functions as List[String] returns Float:
            Let penalty be length of issues * 0.1
            Let exposure_penalty be length of exposed_functions * 0.05
            Return 1.0 - penalty - exposure_penalty

Process called "calculate_function_complexity" that takes source as String returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate cyclomatic complexity from source code analysis
    Let complexity be 1 Note: Base complexity Note: Count decision points for complexity analysis
    If contains_string with text as source and pattern as "if":
            Set complexity to complexity 1
    If contains_string with text as source and pattern as "otherwise":
            Set complexity to complexity 1
    If contains_string with text as source and pattern as "for":
            Set complexity to complexity 1
    If contains_string with text as source and pattern as "while":
            Set complexity to complexity 1
    If contains_string with text as source and pattern as "try":
            Set complexity to complexity 1
    If contains_string with text as source and pattern as "catch":
            Set complexity to complexity 1 Return complexity

Process called "estimate_function_length" that takes frame as TracebackCore.StackFrame returns Integer:
    Note: Estimate function length from available frame information
    Let base_length be 10 Note: Minimum function length
            Let complexity_factor be calculate_function_complexity with source as frame.source_line
            Let variable_factor be length of frame.local_variables
    Let argument_factor be length of frame.arguments Note: Estimate based on complexity and variable count
            Let estimated_length be base_length (complexity_factor * 5) variable_factor argument_factor Return estimated_length

Process called "calculate_complexity_score" that takes total_complexity as Integer and frame_count as Integer returns Float:
    Note: Calculate normalized complexity score
    If frame_count < or equal to 0:
    Return 0.0 Let average_complexity be total_complexity / frame_count Note: Normalize to 0-1 scale (assume max complexity of 20 per function)
    Let normalized_score be average_complexity / 20.0 If normalized_score > 1.0:
            Return 1.0
    Otherwise:
            Return normalized_score

Process called "calculate_maintainability_index" that takes complexity_score as Float and average_length as Integer returns Float:
    Note: Calculate maintainability index based on complexity and length
            Let base_score be 100.0
    Let complexity_penalty be complexity_score * 30.0 Note: Higher penalty for complexity
    Let length_penalty be average_length * 0.2 Note: Penalty for long functions Let maintainability be base_score - complexity_penalty - length_penalty Note: Ensure score stays within 0-100 range
    If maintainability < 0.0:
            Return 0.0
    Otherwise if maintainability > 100.0:
            Return 100.0
    Otherwise:
            Return maintainability

Process called "calculate_cohesion_score" that takes frames as List[TracebackCore.StackFrame] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate cohesion score based on variable sharing between functions
    If length of frames < or equal to 1:
            Return 1.0 Let shared_variables be 0
    Let total_variables be 0 Note: Count shared variables between adjacent frames
    For i from 0 to (length of frames - 2):
            Let current_vars be frames[i].local_variables
    Let next_vars be frames[i 1].local_variables Set total_variables to total_variables length of current_vars For each var_name and var_value in current_vars:
    If var_name in next_vars:
    Set shared_variables to shared_variables 1 If total_variables < or equal to 0:
            Return 0.0 Return shared_variables / total_variables

Process called "calculate_coupling_score" that takes frames as List[TracebackCore.StackFrame] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate coupling score based on function dependencies
    If length of frames < or equal to 1:
            Return 0.0 Let unique_modules be dictionary containing
            Let cross_module_calls be 0
    Let total_calls be length of frames - 1 Note: Track module transitions in call stack
    For i from 0 to (length of frames - 2):
            Let current_module be frames[i].module_name
            Let next_module be frames[i 1].module_name Set unique_modules[current_module] to true
    Set unique_modules[next_module] to true If current_module is not equal to next_module:
    Set cross_module_calls to cross_module_calls 1 If total_calls < or equal to 0:
    Return 0.0 Note: Higher coupling = more cross-module calls
            Return cross_module_calls / total_calls

Process called "detect_circular_dependencies" that takes frames as List[TracebackCore.StackFrame] returns List[List[String]]:
    Note: Detect circular dependencies in call chain
            Let cycles be list containing
            Let module_chain be list containing
    Let seen_modules be dictionary containing For each frame in frames:
    Let module_name be frame.module_name If module_name in seen_modules:
    Note: Found circular dependency
            Let cycle_start be seen_modules[module_name]
    Let cycle be list containing For i from cycle_start to (length of module_chain - 1):
            Add to cycle module_chain[i]
    Add to cycle module_name Note: Complete the cycle Add to cycles cycle Set seen_modules[module_name] to length of module_chain
            Add to module_chain module_name Return cycles

Process called "determine_quality_grade" that takes complexity_score as Float and maintainability_index as Float returns QualityGrade:
    If maintainability_index > 85.0:
            Return Excellent
    Otherwise if maintainability_index > 70.0:
            Return Good
    Otherwise if maintainability_index > 50.0:
            Return Fair
    Otherwise if maintainability_index > 25.0:
            Return Poor
    Otherwise:
            Return Critical

Process called "calculate_crash_probability" that takes performance as PerformanceMetrics and memory as MemoryAnalysis returns Float:
    Let memory_factor be memory.peak_memory_usage_bytes / 1073741824.0 Note: Normalize to GB
    Let performance_factor be performance.total_execution_time_ns / 10000000000.0 Note: Normalize to 10s
            Return (memory_factor plus performance_factor) / 2.0

Process called "calculate_performance_degradation_risk" that takes performance as PerformanceMetrics returns Float:
    If performance.bottleneck_severity = Critical:
            Return 0.9
    Otherwise if performance.bottleneck_severity = Major:
            Return 0.6
    Otherwise if performance.bottleneck_severity = Minor:
            Return 0.3
    Otherwise:
            Return 0.1

Process called "calculate_memory_exhaustion_timeline" that takes memory as MemoryAnalysis returns Integer:
    If memory.memory_growth_rate_bytes_per_second > 0.0:
    Let available_memory be 2147483648 Note: 2GB available
            Let time_to_exhaustion be available_memory / memory.memory_growth_rate_bytes_per_second
            Return time_to_exhaustion
    Otherwise:
    Return 2147483647 Note: Max int (never)

Process called "identify_scalability_limitations" that takes frames as List[TracebackCore.StackFrame] and performance as PerformanceMetrics returns List[String]:
    Let limitations be list containing If performance.recursive_call_depth > 50:
            Add to limitations "Deep recursion may cause stack overflow under load"
    If length of performance.cpu_intensive_functions > 3:
            Add to limitations "Multiple CPU-intensive functions limit parallel processing" Add to limitations "Memory allocation patterns may not scale with increased load"
            Return limitations

Process called "calculate_maintenance_burden" that takes frames as List[TracebackCore.StackFrame] returns Float:
            Let complexity_factor be length of frames / 100.0
            Let diversity_factor be calculate_function_diversity with frames as frames
            Return (complexity_factor plus diversity_factor) / 2.0

Process called "calculate_function_diversity" that takes frames as List[TracebackCore.StackFrame] returns Float:
            Let unique_functions be dictionary containing
    For each frame in frames:
            Set unique_functions[frame.function_name] to true
            Return length of unique_functions / length of frames

Process called "calculate_crash_timeline" that takes performance as PerformanceMetrics and memory as MemoryAnalysis returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate estimated time until potential crash
            Let memory_factor be 1.0
    Let performance_factor be 1.0 Note: Calculate memory pressure factor
    If memory.memory_growth_rate_bytes_per_second > 0.0:
    Let available_memory be 2147483648 - memory.peak_memory_usage_bytes Note: 2GB - current
    If available_memory > 0:
            Set memory_factor to available_memory / memory.memory_growth_rate_bytes_per_second
    Otherwise:
    Set memory_factor to 60 Note: 1 minute if already at limit
    Otherwise:
    Set memory_factor to 86400 Note: 24 hours if no growth Note: Calculate performance degradation factor
    If performance.bottleneck_severity = Critical:
    Set performance_factor to 1800 Note: 30 minutes
    Otherwise if performance.bottleneck_severity = Major:
    Set performance_factor to 7200 Note: 2 hours
    Otherwise:
    Set performance_factor to 86400 Note: 24 hours Note: Return the more pessimistic estimate
    If memory_factor < performance_factor:
            Return memory_factor
    Otherwise:
            Return performance_factor

Process called "calculate_performance_degradation_timeline" that takes performance as PerformanceMetrics returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate timeline for performance degradation
    Let base_timeline be 86400 Note: 24 hours baseline Note: Adjust based on bottleneck severity
    If performance.bottleneck_severity = Critical:
    Return base_timeline / 24 Note: 1 hour
    Otherwise if performance.bottleneck_severity = Major:
    Return base_timeline / 8 Note: 3 hours
    Otherwise if performance.bottleneck_severity = Minor:
    Return base_timeline / 2 Note: 12 hours
    Otherwise:
    Return base_timeline * 7 Note: 7 days Return base_timeline

Process called "calculate_prediction_confidence" that takes issues as List[PredictedIssue] returns Float:
    If length of issues = 0:
            Return 0.0 Let total_confidence be 0.0
    For each issue in issues:
            Set total_confidence to total_confidence issue.probability Return total_confidence / length of issues

Process called "generate_comprehensive_recommendations" that takes performance as PerformanceMetrics and memory as MemoryAnalysis and security as SecurityFindings and quality as QualityAssessment returns List[Recommendation]:
    Let recommendations be list containing Note: Performance recommendations
    If performance.bottleneck_severity = Critical or performance.bottleneck_severity = Major:
    Let rec be Recommendation with:
            category as Performance
            priority as High
            title as "Optimize Performance Bottlenecks"
            description as "Critical performance issues detected requiring immediate attention"
            implementation_steps as list containing "Profile bottleneck functions", "Optimize algorithms", "Consider caching"
            estimated_effort as "2-4 weeks"
            expected_benefit as "50-80% performance improvement"
    code_examples as list containing "Note: Use efficient data structures", "Note: Implement caching"
            related_documentation as list containing "Performance Optimization Guide"
    metadata as dictionary containing "analysis_source" as "performance_metrics" Add to recommendations rec Note: Memory recommendations
    If length of memory.potential_memory_leaks > 0:
    Let rec be Recommendation with:
            category as Memory
            priority as Critical
            title as "Fix Memory Leaks"
            description as "Potential memory leaks detected that could cause application instability"
            implementation_steps as list containing "Review allocation patterns", "Implement proper cleanup", "Add leak detection"
            estimated_effort as "1-2 weeks"
            expected_benefit as "Improved stability and reduced memory usage"
    code_examples as list containing "Note: Proper resource cleanup", "Note: Memory pool usage"
            related_documentation as list containing "Memory Management Best Practices"
    metadata as dictionary containing "analysis_source" as "memory_analysis" Add to recommendations rec Note: Security recommendations
    If security.risk_level = Critical or security.risk_level = High:
    Let rec be Recommendation with:
            category as Security
            priority as Critical
            title as "Address Security Vulnerabilities"
            description as "Critical security issues detected requiring immediate remediation"
            implementation_steps as list containing "Review security findings", "Implement input validation", "Add security tests"
            estimated_effort as "1-3 weeks"
            expected_benefit as "Reduced security risk and improved compliance"
    code_examples as list containing "Note: Input validation", "Note: Secure coding practices"
            related_documentation as list containing "Security Best Practices Guide"
            metadata as dictionary containing "analysis_source" as "security_findings" Add to recommendations rec Return recommendations

Process called "calculate_overall_confidence" that takes performance as PerformanceMetrics and memory as MemoryAnalysis and security as SecurityFindings and quality as QualityAssessment returns Float:
    Note: Calculate overall confidence in analysis results
            Let performance_confidence be if performance.performance_score > 0.5 then 0.9 else 0.6
            Let memory_confidence be if length of memory.potential_memory_leaks > 0 then 0.8 else 0.7
            Let security_confidence be if security.vulnerability_count > 0 then 0.9 else 0.5
            Let quality_confidence be if quality.quality_grade = Excellent or quality.quality_grade = Good then 0.8 else 0.7 Return (performance_confidence memory_confidence security_confidence quality_confidence) / 4.0

